title: For Sale/Trade:  Collectors Grade S&W .38 Victory Model
postcontent:
The Victory model revolvers participated in various roles from guard duty to riding in a shoulder holster with fighter and bomber pilots. I have talked to many ex-military personnel that carried them as late as the 1980s, as you can see these pistols played a significant part of our history. To this day the Victory model is a very enjoyable shooting collectible, mainly due to its inexpensive cost, light recoil, and good accuracy. 

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Victory model was so named for the "V" prefix which was placed before the serial number and represented "Victory" against the Axis powers in World War II. 

Serial numbers for the .38 special Victory model began at about V1 in early 1942 and ran until VS811119 with a date of late August of 1945 (end of production). V1 to approximately V39,999 were predominately .38 S&W Caliber (I have observed revolvers in the 1-40000 range in .38 special caliber).  Serial numbers are located on Inside right grip, frame butt, Cylinder, extractor star, and bottom of barrel. Crane and crane recess are also serial numbered to each other, but this is a different number then the revolvers serial number as is correct for Victory model revolvers. 

The Victory Revolver was produced during World War II, it is a variation of the Military & Police Model of 1905, fourth change and had the following characteristics between 1942 and 1945:

Barrel: 2, 4, 5, or 6 inch. (4 inch common in .38 special, 5 inch common in 38/200 or .38 S&W)
Sights: Fixed
Finish: Early sandblast blue, sandblast mid-night black (appears grayish black). And finally a parkerized finish. Hammer and Trigger are case hardened.
Grips: Checkered walnut with medallion until early 1942, post February of 1942 they are smooth American Walnut with out medallions. 

$500 OBO
Call or Text REDACTED

title: For Sale/Trade:  Benjamin Marauder .22 PCP air rifle w/ scope, pump, etc
postcontent:
The Marauder is one of the best quality hunting air rifles available today, and is good for 30+ full-power shots from its underbarrel pre-compressed cylinder before needing to be refilled.  The cylinder is filled to 3000 psi by means of either a hand pump or a SCUBA tank.  I think the velocity is over 900 fps, but can be adjusted to your preference.  This one is in .22, and they're also available in .177 and .25.

This one, although used, is in excellent shape.  I took it on a trade from a chainsaw customer, but only to get the cash that was owed me out of it.  I've shot it enough to know it's very accurate.  These have more than enough power for squirrel hunting and I've heard enough people claim that they killed a groundhog with one that I can't just call them all liars.  Definitely not the type of air rifle I had as a kid...  

You'll get the rifle itself, which has a Leapers 4-16 x 50mm air rifle scope with red/green illuminated mil-dot reticle and adjustable objective mounted on it.  You'll also get the 10-round rotary magazine and the single-shot adapter, as well as some Benjamin literature and a SCUBA tank adapter.  I also have an Air Force brand 3000 psi hand pump to go with it, and a couple partial tins of .22 pellets.  In short, everything you need to start shooting it is here.

I had to look up pricing before I accepted this as a trade, so here's what this equipment goes for new:

Rifle - About $475
Scope - About $120
Pump - Right at $200
Scope Rings and Pellets - Just along for the ride as part of the deal.

This stuff adds up to around $800 new.  I allowed $600 trade value for it, and I can tell you that with the exception of a couple marks on the scope, it's all in excellent shape.  I've shot it enough that I can show you how it works.  Get into a complete PCP air rifle setup for hundreds less than if you bought new.

This setup is for sale locally only.  I've been contacted by many people asking about shipping it, but honestly it isn't worth the hassle to me.  I don't need the money this minute and am willing to wait for a local sale.  (If you'd like, you're welcome to have a friend of yours that lives near here buy it for you, and they can then ship it to you.)
